

Signature Assessment Report
Background
Canada Life’s 2026 acquisition of Santé Circle Health is the case our group chose to work through this term, and it turned out to be a genuinely good one for testing everything we have learned about enterprise risk management. Canada Life itself is one of Canada’s oldest and most established financial services organizations, founded in 1847 and headquartered in Winnipeg, Manitoba. As a subsidiary of Great-West Lifeco Inc., the company provides insurance, wealth management, and employee benefits solutions to millions of Canadians (Canada Life, 2026a). Santé Circle Health, the company being acquired, is a Canadian provider of disability management services that specializes in absence management, return-to-work programs, and occupational health solutions services that line up naturally with Canada Life’s existing group benefits business (Canada Life, 2026b).
This report brings together everything our group has built across the term the SWOT analysis we developed under an ERM lens, the 18-risk register scored on a 1-to-5 likelihood and impact scale, the Indicators and Warnings (I&W) assessment, and the risk response plan with its associated KRIs into one comprehensive enterprise risk assessment. Our earlier assignments leaned mostly on qualitative judgment backed by secondary research. Here, we push that work further with standardized quantitative modeling, machine learning-based risk prediction, and Monte Carlo simulation, all of it grounded in either our own prior findings or documented industry and regulatory benchmarks rather than arbitrary assumptions.
Mergers and acquisitions are notoriously difficult to pull off well. Research suggests that between 70% and 90% fail to deliver the value shareholders were promised (Bain & Company, 2024), and that number alone tells you why this kind of assessment matters. Canada Life is stepping into active healthcare service delivery for the first time with this deal, which means understanding and managing risk across financial, operational, competitive, reputational, technical, and legal dimensions is not a box-ticking exercise. It is genuinely the difference between an acquisition that strengthens the company’s position and one that turns into an expensive integration failure.
Three things in particular shape the risk landscape we worked through. First, the track record for this kind of deal is not encouraging 70 to 90 percent of M&A transactions fail to create shareholder value, and only about 30 percent hit their projected synergy targets (Bain & Company, 2024). Second, Quebec’s Law 25, fully in force since 2025, sets strict obligations around health data privacy, with penalties that can reach CAD $25 million or four percent of global revenue (OneTrust, 2025). Third, even though Canada Life brings real financial strength to this deal, it is walking into a market where Manulife’s Vitality platform and Sun Life’s digital health investments already give those competitors a head start (KASE Insurance, 2026; HelloSafe, 2025).
Identification of Risks
When we sat down to identify risks for this acquisition, we worked across six dimensions of enterprise risk: financial, operational, competitive, reputational, technical, and legal/regulatory. We used structured brainstorming guided by the COSO ERM risk identification process, drawing on Canada Life’s corporate disclosures, current market intelligence, and regulatory developments. That process, which we originally worked through in our Module 2 and Module 3 assignments, gave us 18 material risks spread across the six categories.
Three risks in particular capture the range of exposure Canada Life is taking on. The first, and the highest-scoring risk in our entire register, is that cross-selling revenue between Canada Life’s existing group benefits clients and Santé Circle Health’s disability management services falls short of what the business case assumes. The second is that a breach of personal health information during the integration period triggers regulatory action under Quebec’s Law 25 and the federal Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act (Government of Canada, 2000) a real concern given that handling sensitive clinical data is Santé Circle Health’s entire business. The third is that legacy system incompatibility between Canada Life’s enterprise insurance platform and Santé Circle Health’s much smaller technology environment disrupts data exchange and clinical service delivery while the two are being merged.
These three risks R-003 (cross-selling synergy shortfall), R-010 (PHI data breach), and R-013 (legacy system incompatibility) are the ones we carried forward into the quantitative analysis in this report. We picked them out of the eight High-priority risks in our register because we had measurable proxy data to work with for each one, and because together they span three distinct risk categories rather than clustering in just one. The full 18-risk register appears in the Qualitative Risk Assessment section below and again in Appendix 1.
Qualitative Risk Assessment
We scored each of the 18 risks on a 1-to-5 scale for both likelihood and impact, then multiplied the two together to get an overall score between 1 and 25. Anything scoring 15 to 25 we classified as High priority, 9 to 14 as Medium, and 1 to 8 as Low. This is the same scoring methodology we used in our Module 3 assignment, and it lines up with the COSO ERM framework (COSO, 2017).
