Industry Fusion Analytics: Validating Risk R-007
Industry Fusion Analytics combines our internal risk register with external competitive intelligence to check whether our qualitative judgments hold up against observable market trends. We put R-007 to this test the risk that Manulife and Sun Life accelerate digital health bundling ahead of Canada Life, which we had qualitatively scored at 16 using a 16-quarter synthetic competitive intelligence panel tracking digital health capability scores for all three companies.
Honestly, the result surprised us, and we decided to report it as it came out rather than quietly adjusting it to match what we originally assumed. The synthetic competitive panel put Canada Life’s most recent digital health capability score at 8.54, against a Manulife/Sun Life average of 7.08 a gap of -1.46 points in Canada Life’s favor, which is the opposite of what we expected going in. Our best guess is that our original qualitative score for R-007 was shaped more by how loudly Manulife markets its Vitality platform (KASE Insurance, 2026) than by the underlying competitive reality, which our synthetic data suggests is more balanced than we initially assumed.
We want to be upfront about what this finding does and does not mean. Our competitive panel is built on synthetic data calibrated to plausible growth trajectories, not actual disclosed competitor metrics, so this isn’t proof that the competitive threat is overstated. What it does tell us is that R-007’s score deserves a second look once real market intelligence is available. That, to us, is the real value of Industry Fusion Analytics it doesn’t replace qualitative judgment, but it stress-tests it and flags the places where our assumptions might need revisiting.
 
