Candidates for Further Quantitative Analysis
Out of the eight High-priority risks, we picked three for full quantitative escalation using the Indicators and Warnings technique: R-003, R-010, and R-013. We chose these based on three things whether we had measurable proxy data to model, whether they covered different risk categories so we weren’t just analyzing one domain repeatedly, and how much a data-driven estimate could realistically add beyond what our qualitative judgment already told us. The other five High-priority risks (R-001, R-002, R-004, R-007, R-017) stay under qualitative monitoring and the KRI framework described later in this report, either because we didn’t have suitable proxy data for them or because the qualitative read already felt solid enough on its own.
Quantitative Risk Assessment
This section walks through the quantitative modeling and ML-based prediction we ran for R-003, R-010, and R-013. We built all the models on synthetic, proxy datasets, since real internal data from Canada Life and Santé Circle Health simply is not available to us. To keep these datasets realistic, we anchored them to documented industry benchmarks the Ponemon Institute’s (2023) breach probability research, IBM Security’s (2023) average breach cost figures, and the parameters from our own Module 3 risk register. The full data generation code and our assumptions are documented in the accompanying GitHub repository (see Appendix 1 for the link).
R-003: Cross-Selling Revenue Synergy Shortfall
The financial case for this acquisition leans heavily on Canada Life’s ability to cross-sell Santé Circle Health’s disability management services into its existing group benefits client base. To test how realistic that plan is, we built a synthetic dataset of 240 cross-sell campaign records, with broker adoption rates, client uptake rates, and revenue per converted client drawn from triangular distributions reflecting plausible ranges for a mid-sized Canadian insurer rolling out a new service line.
Running the statistics on this dataset gave us a mean campaign-level revenue of CAD $194,494, with a standard deviation of CAD $128,305 and a 95% confidence interval of CAD $178,179 to $210,809. When we scaled that campaign-level performance up to Canada Life’s full eligible client base of roughly 12,000 group benefits clients, the projected annual synergy revenue came out to CAD $3,474,638 dramatically below the CAD $18 million Year 1 target baked into the acquisition’s business case.
When we calculated expected loss, variance, and risk exposure against that CAD $18 million target, the gap held up. Expected loss relative to target came out to CAD $14,457,108, with a standard deviation of CAD $1,414,386 and a 95% Value at Risk of CAD $16,392,728. Across all 10,000 simulation iterations, the probability of missing the target was 100%. This is honestly the most important finding in our whole quantitative assessment the original Year 1 synergy target doesn’t look achievable under any of the realistic ranges we tested, which changes R-003 from a risk you monitor into a number that genuinely needs to be renegotiated with the board before the integration goes any further.
 
