R-010: PHI Data Breach — Machine Learning Risk Prediction
To get a read on how vulnerable Canada Life’s integration environment is to a PHI breach, we trained a Random Forest classifier on a synthetic dataset of 500 integration case records. We pulled the features straight from the KRIs in our risk response plan: access control gaps, security training completion percentage, third-party API vetting percentage, data schema mismatches, incident response plan maturity, and encryption coverage percentage.
We validated the model with a stratified 75/25 train-test split plus 5-fold cross-validation. On the held-out test set, the Random Forest hit 88% accuracy, with balanced precision and recall (0.88-0.89) across both the Low Risk and High-Risk classes. A ROC-AUC of 0.963 tells us the model is genuinely good at telling the two classes apart, and 5-fold cross-validation came back consistent at 93.0% (± 1.3%) which is what we wanted to see, since it means the model is learning real patterns rather than just memorizing the synthetic training data.
When we scored a scenario meant to represent Canada Life’s current integration readiness moderate access control gaps, 72% security training completion, 58% third-party API vetting, mid-range incident response maturity the model called it borderline, with a 48.5% estimated breach probability. That number sits right on the edge of the classification threshold, which we read as the model telling us Canada Life is genuinely at a tipping point here, not safely in either camp. The encouraging part is that modest improvements to a couple of the top features the model flagged third-party API vetting and incident response plan maturity especially could realistically push this into Low-Risk territory before integration even begins.
 
Figure 5. Random Forest model validation for R-010: feature importance (left), confusion matrix (center), and ROC curve (right).
R-013: Legacy System Incompatibility — Machine Learning Risk Prediction
For R-013, we trained a Gradient Boosting classifier on that same synthetic integration dataset, this time using features aligned to the technical KRIs from our risk response plan: API coverage gap percentage, data schema mismatches, manual workaround volume, legacy system age, integration test pass rate, and IT staff readiness score.
This model came back with 89% accuracy on the held-out test set, a ROC-AUC of 0.964, and 5-fold cross-validation accuracy of 89.2% (± 2.0%) about the same validation strength as the Random Forest model we used for R-010. The feature importance results confirmed what our Module 3 reasoning already suspected: API coverage gaps and data schema mismatches are the strongest predictors of system incompatibility, by a clear margin.
When we scored Canada Life’s current integration scenario a 35% API coverage gap, 11 data schema mismatches, 78 manual workarounds per week, and a 12-year-old legacy system the model came back with a 94.0% probability of significant system incompatibility. That’s a decisive High-Risk classification, and it’s considerably worse than the qualitative score alone suggested. What this tells us is that the technical integration between Canada Life and Santé Circle Health is going to need a lot more pre-close due diligence and a longer phased migration than a typical integration of this size would normally call for.
 
